definition.value: An iron coordination entity containing one iron unit and two nitrogen oxide units. Acts to store and transport NO.
A tetrahydroxyflavone that is flavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 5, 7 and 4' and a 4-methyl-5-oxopyrrolidin-2-yl group at position 8.

A tertiary amino compound that consists of cyclohexane having piperidin-1-yl and thiophen-2-yl groups attached at position 1. A dissociative anaesthetic drug with halluccinogenic and stimulant effects. Its effects are similar to those of phencyclidine (PCP, an analogue with the thienyl group replaced by phenyl), but it is rather more potent.
A lipid similar in structure to a glycerolipid but in which one or more of the carbon atoms on glycerol is bonded to an alkyl chain via an ether linkage, as opposed to the usual ester linkage.
An optically active phosphatidylethanolamine zwitterion having R-configuration
Any optically active triglyceride that has R-configuration.

A pectin polymer characterized by a backbone of alpha-(1-4)-linked D-galacturonic acid residues substituted with apiose and apiobiose (D-apiofuranosyl-beta-(1-3)-D-apiose) side chains via O-2 or O-3 links.
Any of a group of guanidine or amidine phosphates that function as storage depots for high-energy phosphate in muscle with the purpose of regenerating ATP from ADP during muscular contraction.
A nucleoside phosphate consisting of a purine base linked to a ribose sugar esterified with one phosphate group attached to each of two different hydroxy groups on the sugar.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is an O-glucosylated derivative of quercetin.
A soluble alpha-D-glucan with mainly alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkages but with also significant amounts of alpha(1->6) and alpha(1->4,6) linkages.
Any monocarboxylic acid containing fully saturated C-C bonds.

A 43-membered microcin composed of Val, Gly, Ile, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Ser, Cys, Gly, Gly, Gln, Gly, Gly, Gly, Cys, Gly, Gly, Cys, Ser, Asn, Gly, Cys, Ser, Gly, Gly, Asn, Gly, Gly, Ser, Gly, Gly, Ser, Gly, Ser, His and Ile residues joined in sequence.
A polymer containing chains of uronic acids and N-acetylglucosamine found in the cell wall, membrane or capsule of Gram-positive bacteria.
A class of gene-encoded low-molecular-mass antibacterial peptides secreted by enterobacteria.

A fourteen-membered heterodetic cyclic peptide comprising the sequence Ala-Gly-Cys-Lys-Asn-Phe-Phe-Trp-Lys-Thr-Phe-Thr-Ser-Cys cyclised by a disulfide bridge between the two Cys residues at positions 3 and 14.
An organoiodine compound that is amphetamine bearing two methoxy substituents at positions 2 and 5 as well as an iodo substituent at position 4.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide that consists of the linear trisaccharide alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine having an alpha-L-fucosyl residue attached at the 2-position of the central galactose.

A conjugated form of indole-3-acetic acid.  There are two types of indoleacetic acid conjugates: ester and amide conjugates. The ester conjugates are formed with sugars or polyols through an ester bond, whereas the amide conjugates are formed with amino acids or polypeptides through an amide bond.
A conjugate of indole-3-acetic acid with amino acids or polypeptides via an amide bond.
A conjugate of indole-3-acetic acid with sugars or polyols via an oxygen bridge.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is an O-glucosylated derivative of kaempferol.
A C-nitro compound that is imidazole bearing a nitro substituent at position 5.

A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta position with a deprotonated sulfo group.  Derived from the parent diazonium compound, it is commonly involved in conjugate formation with proteins.
A repetitive glycan polysaccharide contained within a lipopolysaccharide (LPS). The O-antigen is attached to the core oligosaccharide, and comprises the outermost domain of the LPS molecule.
A phenylazo group is a group formed from a substituted or unsubstituted phenyldiazene or benzenediazonium compound, with the free valence at the terminal nitrogen.
An amino-acid residue derived from O-(alpha-D-mannose-1-phosphoryl)-L-serine. A modified serine residue.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from hypusine.
An inorganic cation with a valency of two.
An amino-acid cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and protonation of the two amino groups of (3R)-3-methyl-D-ornithine; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and protonation of the three amino groups of N(6)-[(3R)-3-methyl-D-ornithyl]-L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta position with a glycinocarbonyl group.

A peptide of 36-43 amino acids that is processed from the amyloid precursor protein. Appears to be the main constituent of amyloid plaques (deposits found in the brains of Alzheimer's disease patients).

A beta-amyloid that is a 40 amino acid polypeptide of sequence Asp Ala Glu Phe Arg His Asp Ser Gly Tyr Glu Val His His Gln Lys Leu Val Phe Phe Ala Glu Asp Val Gly Ser Asn Lys Gly Ala Ile Ile Gly Leu Met Val Gly Gly Val Val.

A beta-amyloid that ia a 42 amino acid polypeptide of sequence Asp Ala Glu Phe Arg His Asp Ser Gly Tyr Glu Val His His Gln Lys Leu Val Phe Phe Ala Glu Asp Val Gly Ser Asn Lys Gly Ala Ile Ile Gly Leu Met Val Gly Gly Val Val Ile Ala.
A class of six-membered cyclodepsipeptides found in several species of Fusarium fungi as mixtures.
An enniatin obtained from formal cyclocondensation of three N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-valine units.
An enniatin obtained from formal cyclocondensation of one N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-leucine and two N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-valine units.
An enniatin obtained from formal cyclocondensation of three N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-isoleucine units.
An enniatin obtained from formal cyclocondensation of one N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-valine and two N-[(2R)-2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoyl]-N-methyl-L-isoleucine units.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the ortho position with a deprotonated carboxy group.
The nucleoside residue formed from guanosine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
The nucleoside residue formed from 2'-O-methylguanosine with linkages at the 2' and 5' positions.
The nucleoside residue formed from cytidine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
The nucleoside residue formed from 2'-O-methylcytidine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta position with a deprotonated carboxy group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the para position with a deprotonated carboxy group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the ortho position with a monodeprotonated arsono group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the ortho position with a deprotonated sulfo group.
